==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lollard
<hw>Lol"lard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>Lollardi</ets>, <ets>Lullardi</ets>, from Walter
<ets>Lolhardus</ets>, a German; cf. LG. & D. <ets>lollen</ets> to
mumble, to hum, sing in a murmuring strain; hence, OD.
<ets>lollaerd</ets> a mumbler, <it>i. e.</it>, of prayers or psalms,
which was prob. the origin of the name. See <er>Loll</er>,
<er>Lull</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One of
a sect of early reformers in Germany.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the
followers of Wyclif in England.</def> <altsp>[Called also
<asp>Loller</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>Lollards</qex> all know the Wyclifities are meant, so
called from <person>Walter Lollardus</person>, one of their teachers in
Germany.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lollardy</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Lollardism</ent>⟦br⟧
